  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Medical practice &amp; training are inherently stressful situations. However, the effects of
      stress on educational &amp; clinical performance are not well defined. The purpose of the current
      study is to examine the effects of stress on performance of residents in simulated trauma
      scenarios. The hypothesis is: 1) acutely stressful scenarios will be appraised as threat by
      residents and result in elevations of heart rate and salivary cortisol; 2) increased
      subjective &amp; physiological stress will result in impairments in performance; and 3) greater
      stress responses will result in greater clinical impairments.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
